review_blob: Good with Asian food, obviously, but not something I would have in another situation. Refreshing.
My go-to party beer. Goes down easy and is refreshing, but still tastes better than most of the alternatives.
Golden pour, mildly caramel on the taste with a small bit of spicing. Light hops. Decent.
Amber with a white head. Barley taste with sweet malts. Mild but pretty refreshing overall.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Bright gold pour with a white head. Apricoty with some vanilla elements. Really good. The caps are cool too.
Malty taste, but with a complex (probably because I cant really explain it) finish. An old favorite of mine.
Chocolatey in the best possible way. Sat down with a six of these and a bag of M&M;s and had myself a feast.
If Corona is 5 parts water, 1 part beer, then LandShark is 4 parts water, 2 parts beer. Not recommended.
A good party beer, if youre going to be drinking a ton of them. Not very good in any other situation.
Yellow pour on the hazy side, thin head. Citrus, lime-like aroma with sugary smell. Great beer.
beer_name: Florida Beer Key West Southernmost Wheat

review_blob: Pale lager, thin head, a bit watery. Good for drinking at the club, or if youre in the fuckin zone.
Definite must at a Japanese restaurant, but otherwise pretty forgettable unless Sake bombing. Malty aroma, crisp with very light (almost undetectable) flavor.
Crisp lager taste, but a bit on the pricey side. Golden yellow pour, slightly watery. Hoppy taste by lager standards.
Its worthwhile for the novelty of the supersized can. Pale color with skunky aroma. Flavor not very enjoyable, but an easily drinkable beer nonetheless.
It was pretty bizarre seeing a palm tree on a "Traditional German Style" beer, but I gave it a try anyway. Pale yellow. Not very good.
An extremely drinkable beer with a yellow pour. I would recommend it. Easily found.
Good if youre drinking a whole lot of them, and thats about it. A bit like flavored water.
The ultimate American throw-back-a-few-during-slowpitch beer. Everyone knows what this ones all about.
Golden pour with a pretty small head. Aroma is citrusy. Interesting amount of hops for a summer ale. Great taste.
Not a fan. Went into it pretty optimistic, since Im a fan of Becks usually, but this is just poodle piss.
Pale yellow lager, light flavor but a skunky aftertaste which I personally enjoyed. A pretty quenching beer.

Amber color with clouds. Big head. Caramel and inviting aroma, but to me it just tasted skunky. Perhaps it was the six pack I picked up, as after reading the rest of these reviews it appears that its a great beer... I just didnt get that.
Great go-to beer for parties, pretty much everyones had it so they know the deal. Gets the job done in a classier way than most party beers. Great for beirut.
Dark brown pour, definitely taste the carmel and sugar tastes, but also a hint of a coffee-like aftertaste. Would be good with a dessert or something chocolate. Hides the 7.2% ABV, which is awesome.
A little bit of a skunky aroma, tastes full of hops and a bit of citrus. Not an everyday beer, but a nice once-in-a-while middle-of-the-pack kind.
Orange and lime hints in the flavor, a bit like a weaker original BM. Not very impressive or otherwise remarkable.
beer_name: Blue Moon Rising Moon Spring Ale

review_blob: Very little head, resembles your typical pale lager, taste is watery Heineken. Grab one at a BBQ or something to tone down the spiciness of your food without wasting a good beer.
Highly refreshing, a little bit of a copper/nickely finish, but balanced. Everyones pretty familiar with Bass, so no need to go crazy defining it. Worthwhile.

Had this on tap where I worked last summer, would be lying if I said I didnt sneak a few now and again. Smells good, looks even better, but the taste is pretty soft and disappointing-- I guess thats to be expected for a summer brew. Not my favorite, but not bad.

Great head (I know, I know, thats what she said) with this one, which lasts surprisingly long and even shoots out of the bottle a little. Sweetness to the taste thats inviting, great when its ice cold. Overall, a great Sam Adams.

Contains a rocket widget, which in and of itself is usually pretty cool no matter how good the beer is. Thick head, almost comically so. Malty and smooth, easily drinkable, but sits pretty heavy. Caramel aftertaste.
White head, bitter and hoppy like most IPAs, light in feel, great overall. Definitely a worthwhile pickup.
A good winter brew, not as heavy as its relatives. Definitely can taste the regular Blue Moon in it, but this has a lot more of a sweetness to it. Extremely drinkable.
beer_name: Blue Moon Full Moon Winter Ale

review_blob: Amber appearance, citrus-y aroma, shades of raisins almost. Smooth taste of hops and malts, kinda bitter. Good but not remarkable.
Tastes just like a pumpkin pie, and smells equally delicious. Not something I could drink more than a couple of at a time, but still pretty nice.

Pretty disappointed by its unremarkable flavor. Seemed a little off-balance in my opinion, not enough hops. Surprised by its effervescence after opening it, as the carbonation wasnt visible through the bottle. Not a repeat.
Only had it once, and that was one time too many. This is really little more than cold bile in a can.
A mild improvement over its Light counterpart, but thats a little like saying a foot amputation is better than a leg amputation.
Ol reliable: the go-to drink of highschool parties for its affordability and easiness to drink. Does the job. Nothing taste-wise to write about.
Really, truly, I cannot stress how godawful this beer is. Worth it only to get drunk, and in that case I recommend bonging so as to avoid tasting it for too long.
Clear body, small head. Malty and hoppy, but not overwhelmingly so. Somewhat ordinary, but definitely refreshing.
I thought I had already rated this one. Definitely reminiscent of most Belgian/North German brews Ive had. Refreshing and pleasing, though admittedly simple. Worthwhile and non-filling.
Pretty unremarkable, and a bit disappointing actually. Taste is bitter and flat, disappears almost immediately and replaces itself with a strongly undesirable aftertaste.
Small head, hints of malt and spices, a little different taste than the original, but not enough to really delve into detail about.
Great with Mexican food or on a hot day. Usually pop one open when Im doing lawn work. Hint of hops, very simple brew. Nothing to write home about.
Watered down Heineken. Not even close to worthwhile, and still just as expensive as the original!
Not really sure why theres even a market for a Corona Light, as the original is far from filling. Tolerable only with a lime, and even then, Id sooner drink the ocean water.

Like most Mexican beers, better with a lime. Refreshing like none other after a day in the sun. You dont drink this for the complexity, and if thats the only element of a beer that you enjoy, youre probably a pompous idiot anyway.
Pretty weak. Overall made me wish for a fuller taste. Hints of spices, overall extremely smooth. Gets you drunk, but not in an enjoyable way.
UPDATED: NOV 27, 2007
